<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Milk row may force Tesco to buy from Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tesco, the UK supermarket chain, yesterday threatened to source a
significant proportion of the company's dairy products from the Continent if
the government does not change plans for opening up the Pounds 3.3bn British
milk market that are leading to large increases in price.
The threat, made by Tesco's trading director Mr John Gildersleeve, came as
Mr William Waldegrave, the agriculture minister, rejected calls from the
Dairy Trade Federation for a referral of the planned milk market to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The Dairy Trade Federation, which represents British dairy companies, will
apply for a judicial review of the milk market liberalisation on Monday.
Mr Chris Haskins, chairman of Northern Foods, one of the UK's largest dairy
groups, said he was disappointed at Mr Waldegrave's decision. Northern
claims market changes could wipe Pounds 15m off its profits this year.
Avonmore Foods, the Irish dairy group, made a profits warning yesterday and
Unigate has also told the City to expect its results to be affected.
Mr Gildersleeve called the deregulation plans 'a retrograde step of the
worst order, which is inflationary and leading to price increases of 20 per
cent'. He was speaking at the launch of Tesco's Best of British promotion,
aimed at encouraging shoppers to buy home-produced goods.
The Milk Marketing Board, the government's statutory purchaser of milk in
England and Wales, is due to be abolished at the beginning of November when
the market is liberalised. It will be replaced by Milk Marque, a voluntary
farmers' co-operative, which has already signed up 65 per cent of supplies.
Milk Marque's price auction for allocating supplies to dairies has led to a
jump in price of between 10 per cent and 18 per cent for different types of
buyers.
Mr Gildersleeve said he would have no choice but to buy products from
outside the UK, which would reverse much of the government's efforts of
recent years in encouraging supermarkets to buy British in a bid to reduce
the Pounds 5.6bn food and drink trade gap.
Tesco used to buy fromage frais from France, but in the past couple of years
had turned to British suppliers, Mr Gildersleeve said. But if there is to be
a 20 per cent price increase he said he would be forced to go back to buying
from the Continent.
Mr Jim McMichael-Phillips, DTF president, said imports would flood into the
new market. 'For Milk Marque to suggest that its pricing strategy will
provide the industry with security and stability in the open market is
totally irresponsible,' he said.
</TEXT>
