FT  09 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Although the autumn season is grinding into gear, there are still lots of
repeats, especially on BBC2 which manages only 15 minutes of original matter
between 5.30 and 9.00. Some of the old stuff is retro-telly, kitsch nonsense
such as Captain Scarlet And The Mysterons which broadcasters like to call
'cult' series. This implies passionate dedication but usually means that
only a few people actually want to watch. At 9.00 on BBC2 comes World Cup
Athletics, which, for me, will be a meeting too far. Linford Christie's poor
showing since the Commonwealth Games suggests that television's keenness to
promote the sport has resulted in too many meetings. BBC2's most interesting
programme promises to be The Longest Walk, in which Janet Street-Porter
joins Ffyona Campbell on the final stages of her journey. It is tempting
because Campbell's mother describes her as pig-headed and her former support
driver as horrible (10.00). Two other programmes also depend upon strong
characters making journeys: Tom Vernon in Fat Man In France (7.30 BBC1); and
John Betjeman in The Lost Betjemans (8.00 C4).
