<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Softer stance to trench digging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ground containing buried electrical cables or gas pipes is usually dug up by
hand to avoid damage by the hard-cutting teeth of conventional excavators.
Concept Engineering Group, a Pittsburgh-based engineering company, has
designed a trench-digging machine that avoids damaging cables and pipes by
using supersonic jets of air to crumble the soil, after which the soil is
scooped up using a vacuum system.
The system, which was designed for the Electric Power Research Institute of
California, is now being modified in the hope that it can be used for
environmental waste clean-ups and bulk material handling.
Concept Engineering Group: US, tel 412 826 3191.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3531 Construction Machinery.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
