<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Controls urged on forensic 'cowboys'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW DERRINGTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anybody can act as an expert witness and give forensic evidence, provided
they can convince a court of their expertise, Ms Christine Willmore, a
lawyer from Bristol University told the meeting.
Dr Janet Thompson, director-general of the Forensic Science Service, said
there was no way to prevent 'cowboy' forensic scientists from acting as
expert witnesses.
What is needed, according to Dr Angela Gallop, a forensic adviser, is 'a
proper statutory body with teeth' that will accredit expert witnesses to
deal with particular areas of evidence.
Dr Gallop said people are setting themselves up as expert witnesses to give
evidence on areas that they do not really understand, and many courtroom
disagreements between expert witnesses are the result of lack of experience.
The only way to become expert in a particular area is to spend years working
in a forensic laboratory, she said. One problem is the need for both
prosecution and defence solicitors to keep costs down.
Dr Thompson said discussions had been going on for 2 1/2 years to establish
a voluntary accreditation scheme for forensic science laboratories, and
National Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) that will recognise the competence
of expert witnesses.
</TEXT>
