<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Retail sales growth slows again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The annual rate of growth of retail sales in Britain slowed in August for
the second month in succession, the Confederation of British Industry said
yesterday, fostering hopes that the Treasury and Bank of England will delay
any planned increase in UK bank base rates.
The CBI said its latest survey of 449 companies with 15,000 outlets in the
retail, wholesale and motor trades came up with the slowest year-on-year
rate of growth for high-street sales since retailers first reported rising
volumes in January 1993.
The poll, which covered 266 retailers between August 16 and September 1,
found 31 per cent reporting a sales increase compared with a year ago, 29
per cent a decrease, and 39 per cent no change. The resulting positive
balance of 2 per cent, which the CBI considers indicative of the trend, was
lower than July's positive balance of 12 per cent and June's 27 per cent.
It also confounded expectations the previous month that August would see a
sharper increase in sales. The CBI reported that 30 per cent of retailers
found sales poor for the time of year compared with only 15 per cent saying
they were good. On balance, retailers cut employment in August compared with
the year before and plan further cuts.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's distributive trades panel, said
the slowdown 'was perhaps not surprising' because sales grew strongly in
August last year. But he said retailers had been unable to raise prices as
much as they expected, indicating tough competitive conditions.
While retailers struggled, the 123 wholesalers surveyed reported a strong
increase in sales volumes in the year to August and sales well above average
for the time of year.
Wholesalers have been performing well since the late spring of last year.
Although they supply goods directly to institutions such as schools,
hospitals and local authorities, they are becoming increasingly independent
of the retail trade. But the wholesalers' strong trading performance did not
prevent a fall in employment in the year to August and expectations of a
further drop this month. Wholesalers also expect to cut investment slightly
in the months ahead.
Although the motor trades reported an increase in sales in the year to
August, the positive balance of 9 per cent was much less than expected.
Motor traders reported their second poorest sales performance this year. The
modest increase in volumes largely reflected increased sales of parts and
accessories.
In spite of generally disappointing results, most retail sectors reported
annual growth in sales, with off-licensees reporting the strongest volume
increases for the third month running. Mail-order houses and large multiple
outlets continued to do better than small multiple and single outlets, which
reported sales virtually flat in the year to August.
All three distributive trades expect business to improve over the next three
months. But Mr Whittaker said expectations have not been fully realised in
the last two surveys.
