<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Lasers can clean dirty buildings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lasers can clean the dirty faces of old buildings more effectively than the
conventional methods of blasting with abrasive powder or high-pressure
water, the British Association meeting heard.
Although building conservators have been talking for 20 years about using
lasers to remove industrial grime, practical and affordable systems are only
now coming into use, said Mr John Larson of National Museums and Galleries
on Merseyside. He heads the first UK project to develop a laser for cleaning
buildings and sculpture.
The system has been tested successfully on patches of delicate stone carving
on Lincoln and Salisbury cathedrals and on the terracotta exterior of the
Henry Cole wing at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London. The V&amp;A now
plans to raise money from the Millennium Fund to clean the whole Henry Cole
wing by laser.
Lasers have been used more extensively in Italy and France, including
cleaning the whole front of Amiens cathedral.
The crust of dirt on stone or other material 'absorbs laser energy, which
swells the dirt, lifts it off the surface and partly vaporises it,' Mr
Larson said. 'When the laser reaches the clean surface, all the energy is
reflected back and the conservator can rely on it not to remove any more
material.'
That is one advantage over conventional abrasive techniques, which are
liable to remove some undamaged material with the dirt, according to Mr
Larson. Another is that it avoids the creation of large amounts of mess and
debris.
National Museums and Galleries on Merseyside is negotiating with an unnamed
American company to commercialise the system. Each one is likely to cost in
the region of Pounds 25,000 to Pounds 30,000.
As Mr Larson pointed out, it would be an unusual step for a public museum to
develop a product in this way in collaboration with the private sector. 'Our
trustees are very keen to go ahead - and at the same time nervous about it,'
he said.
He and his colleagues are also working on an ultra-violet laser for cleaning
and removing varnish from paintings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7349 Building Maintenance Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
