FT  09 SEP 94 / Minister spells out vision for science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Hunt, science minister, spelled out his 'vision to move science,
engineering and technology into the mainstream of our education system, our
culture and our public debate' to the British Association yesterday.
He emphasised the need for scientists to communicate better and announced
grants worth a total of Pounds 375,000 to promote public understanding -
Pounds 150,000 for the Royal Society's Committee on the Public Understanding
of Science, Pounds 140,000 for the British Association to organise a
National Week of Science next year, and Pounds 85,000 for a Science Museum
mobile exhibition on 'the information superhighway'.
Mr Hunt promised that he would make use of his position as Chancellor of the
Duchy of Lancaster - and chairman of several key cabinet economic committees
 -'to keep science at the heart of government'.
He was cautiously optimistic about the prospects for an increase in the
government science budget when next year's public spending plans are
announced at the end of November.
The prime minister's statement early this year that science would be a high
priority for future funding 'is going to be very helpful' in the coming
round of public expenditure negotiations, Mr Hunt said.
