<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / CBI may shift on EU social policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, is to meet Mr John Monks, TUC
general secretary, later this month in a move which could lead to a
significant shift in the CBI's attitude to the European Union's agenda on
social affairs.
Many larger members of the Confederation of British Industry with interests
in mainland Europe believe the organisation cannot afford to sit on the
sidelines as others decide on EU social policy that affects them.
The two men intend to search for common ground that would enable the CBI to
participate fully in the 'social dialogue' approach in Brussels on
employment issues.
The social dialogue approach is being developed with the encouragement of
the European Commission by Unice, the European employers' federation, and
the ETUC union federation.
The social dialogue approach involves negotiation between employers and
unions at EU level of framework agreements as an alternative to the
imposition of legally enforceable directives.
The CBI was involved earlier this year in an attempt to negotiate a
framework agreement on European works councils, but pulled out of the Unice
negotiating team as a result of pressure from its smaller and medium-sized
members.
A growing number of the CBI's large affiliates want the organisation to take
part in European decision-making in spite of the government's opt-out from
the social chapter of the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Jacques Santer, the new EU president, is to speak at the CBI's annual
conference this autumn.
Some CBI officials say they are not opposed in principle to involvement in
the social dialogue at European level. They do not believe this would
conflict either with British employment law or the industrial relations
system.
But the CBI would like to see a much longer timetable than at present for
considering issues under the social dialogue, which now involves a process
of two periods of six weeks within three months to reach agreement.
Union leaders are willing to try to reach agreement with the CBI on European
social issues. Mr Bill Jordan, the AEEU engineering union president, who is
due to speak at the CBI's conference this autumn, has invited the CBI to
discuss with the TUC a framework agreement on life-long training.
</TEXT>
