<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Earthmovers take over from explosives: Jimmy Burns sees the
'unarmed struggle' on the Irish border
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was the smallest of streams - a burn not more than a foot wide. Yet in
the context of Northern Ireland's turbulent politics, it had momentarily
achieved near-biblical proportions.
The stream, which passes under a country road seven miles from Londonderry,
separates north and south Ireland. Early this week the spot was chosen by
republicans to demonstrate what they now call the 'unarmed phase of the
struggle' for Irish unity.
At around 5pm, republicans in cars and vans met local farmers and builders
with farming and earth-moving equipment on the north side of the border.
The fittest among them began with the help of a bulldozer to move a series
of small concrete bollards blocking the road into nearby fields.
Then they moved down the road towards the south and tried to move some
larger blocks which marked the border.
When they failed they laid a temporary road to one side of the blocks so
that vehicles could cross the border.
The barriers were set up by the security forces during the 1970s to stop
terrorists using isolated roads to cross the border. Although occasionally
inspected by army patrols, they never became permanent checkpoints.
But following last week's ceasefire announcement by the IRA, they have
become the target of political action.
Sinn Fein officials in Londonderry see the removal of the barriers as part
of the demilitarisation process and, more importantly, a symbol of their
commitment to Irish unity. They do not accept that removing them without the
consent of the security forces is illegal.
So far the removal of the barriers has been carried out in an air of
celebration rather than confrontation, although tension has never been far
beneath the surface.
Near the stream, the demonstrators - men, women and children - laughed as
the oldest republican present, former Sinn Fein councillor Barney McFadden,
cut a makeshift tape of kitchen towelling and declared the border crossing
permanently opened.
'Tell me, Patrick, is the grass greener now on the other side?' joked one
republican to another as demonstrators stepped from north to south and back
again.
The security forces were not present. They have been replacing the barriers
 -in the early hours of the morning, after the demonstrators have left.
Nevertheless the border 'opening' I witnessed had been kept secret until the
last minute, and to attend it I had to be accompanied by a Sinn Fein member.
The good humour gave way to defiance when some of the demonstrators were
intercepted later by a heavily armed Ulster police patrol and subjected to
intensive document checks.
Neither the barriers nor the checks had 'absolutely any justification,' said
Mr Martin McGuinness, Londonderry's most prominent republican figure, who is
believed to have played a key role in ensuring the acceptance of the IRA
ceasefire.
Mr McGuinness himself called for checkpoints to be removed together with the
'other paraphernalia of war' in and around 'one of the most heavily
garrisoned cities in the world'. The security presence in the area includes
heavily fortified police and army barracks and watchtowers with long-range
camera equipment.
The republican 'unarmed struggle' is being watched nervously, however, not
just by the security forces but by the Protestant community.
For a people to whom history often seems like only yesterday, the current
campaign of civil action - including picketing police stations in protest at
alleged harassment of Catholics by security forces - is reminiscent of the
early stages of the conflict.
Republican sources insist the IRA ceasefire has been agreed to in a
time-frame generous enough to allow for genuine political and constitutional
progress to be made in the framework of the current Anglo-Irish peace
process.
But no republican I talked to in Londonderry would guarantee that military
operations had ended for ever. Several insisted the ceasefire would hold as
long as the government responded by taking more than just cosmetic steps to
demilitarisation in Catholic areas.
Their demands range from a withdrawal of army patrols to the gradual
introduction in Catholic areas of a reformed and retrained police force,
which is still regarded as sectarian. Beyond this, there is the sine qua non
of political concession.
Down on the Bogside, there is a freshly-painted mural. It shows a British
soldier carrying the Union Jack on his back and walking off down a country
road - a road clearly signposted to London.
</TEXT>
