<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Financial advisers to campaign on costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new trade association for independent financial advisers was launched
yesterday, with the promise to campaign for its members on issues such as
rising regulatory costs, Alison Smith writes.
There has been concern among independent financial advisers that their
interests were in danger of being lost compared with the lobbying strength
of large life-insurance companies.
The IFA Association has been formed from the National Federation of
Independent Financial Advisers, which had about 2,000 members, and a further
1,200 advisers who were in the financial-services element of the British
Insurance and Investment Brokers' Association. It hopes to have about 4,000
members by the end of the year. Its chief executive is Mr Garry Heath,
formerly chief executive of the national federation.
The association will represent the sector's views to regulators, the
government and other organisations, such as consumer groups. Its first
campaigns will focus on the costs of regulation, arrangements for paying
compensation to customers who have suffered poor advice on pension
transfers, and the rising cost of professional indemnity insurance.
It will also highlight the potential threat to the widespread availability
of independent financial advice if hundreds of advisers do not apply to join
the Personal Investment Authority, the new regulator to protect the private
investor.
</TEXT>
