<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / S African ministers criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOWETO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The head of the communist allies of President Nelson Mandela's governing
party hit out yesterday at the big salaries earned by South Africa's new
rulers, Reuter reports from Soweto.
Mr Charles Nqakula, general secretary of the South African Communist party,
told trade union activists that the new rulers were in danger of
representing only the bosses. 'It is scandalous that such huge amounts of
money are squandered,' he told a meeting of the Congress of South African
Trade Unions, an umbrella group with close ties to the communists. 'We
pledge to continue the struggle. . . against the gravy train in the upper
echelons of the public sector,' he added.
The 'gravy train' comment hits a raw nerve in Mr Mandela's four-month-old
government, which has been accused by such respected figures as Archbishop
Desmond Tutu of enriching itself in the same way as the old white
administrations.
