<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / Berliners say goodbye to Allies: US, British and French
leaders see military presence come to an end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Leaders of Allied countries joined nostalgic Berliners yesterday as the last
American, British and French troops bad farewell to the city after
protecting it for nearly 50 years.
'It will be so difficult to forget the Allies, especially the Americans.
They bombed us during the second world war but in 1948 they dropped parcels
full of food. They kept us alive,' said Mr Helmut Bischof, a 76-year-old
former engineer in the German air force.
The day's events were presided over by Chancellor Helmut Kohl and attended
by President Francois Mitterrand of France, Mr John Major, the British prime
minister, and Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state. At a ceremony at
the Luftbrucken memorial at Tempelhof airport in the south of the city, they
took the salute from units of each of the four countries.
At Tempelhof on June 25, 1948, General Lucius Clay, commander of the US
forces in Berlin, ordered 'Operation Vittles', a massive airlift designed to
feed the west Berliners after Stalin had attempted to take over the entire
city through starving into submission people living in the sectors
controlled by the US, British and French.
'Stalin had tried to intimidate the Berliners. But the resolve of the Allies
and the Berliners' prevented this, said Mr Christopher.
'I remember the airlift so well,' said Mrs Barbara Wagner, an 82-year-old
pensioner. 'On the night of June 23, the lights over our city went out. We
thought we would fall into the hands of the communists. But a few days
later, we heard the hum of Allied aircraft swooping down on Berlin. That was
the best sound I had ever heard in my entire life. I never wanted that sound
to leave the skies over my city.'
Mr Christopher recalled how, at the peak of the airlift, aircraft were
landing every 90 seconds. 'Two million tonnes of supplies were delivered to
Berlin. The roaring engines provided Berliners with hope and reassurance,'
he added.
Mr Kohl, speaking earlier at the Schauspielhaus concert hall in east Berlin,
said when he first visited Berlin in 1947, 'I was 17 years old. . . the city
lay in ruins, the future was uncertain. For almost half a century the three
western Allies protected and defended freedom here in Berlin, in the heart
of our continent.'
The older generation of Berliners regret the departure of the Allies. But
their military presence in the city had already been sharply reduced under
the terms of the unification treaty. The housing, barracks and sport grounds
will revert to the German state, which last year paid nearly DM1bn (Pounds
400m) for the upkeep of the troops. And Berliners, for the first time since
the unification of Germany in 1871, will no longer require an army to subdue
them, or defend them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
