<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Mercury set to offer cheaper mobile calls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury One-2-One, the mobile phone operator, is set to increase competition
in the business telecommunications market today with a new daytime service
undercutting prices charged by British Telecommunications.
The service, which will be available only within the M25 area initially, is
likely to offer One-2-One callers prices of up to 15 per cent below BT's,
provided they make their calls from within a narrow designated area.
When One-2-One launched its network last autumn it offered free local calls
in the evening in a bid to sell itself to consumers deterred by the expense
of mobile phones.
The new service is an attempt to spread the same message to the medium- and
small-business sector, which has until now also been wary of cellular
phones.
The overall cost of joining the One-2-One network is significantly higher
than that charged by BT. Its cellular handsets retail at Pounds 200 or more,
with annual connection and subscription charges of a similar order.
However, One-2-One's move is set to stimulate greater competition between
the UK's four mobile phone net-works.
Pressure will be strong on the other network operators - Vodafone, Cellnet
and Orange - to respond with price cuts, although they trade on the wider
geographical coverage that is available on their networks.
One-2-One, a joint venture between Mercury Communications and US West, a
regional US phone company, launched its network a year ago and has about
120,000 subscribers. The UK's four cellular networks together have about
2.7m subscribers.
</TEXT>
