<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Second-tier data fail to
effect sentiment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue chips retreated yesterday, but technology issues forged ahead in spite
of a sagging bond market, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 12.45 off at 3,886.25, near to its
worst level of the day. But the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was
down just 0.90 at 470.96. By the close the Big Board was showing nearly as
many rising issues as falls.
After Tuesday's sluggish session, New York SE volume picked up to a fairly
active 292m shares, even though many investors were taking the day off in
observance of Rosh Hashanan, the Jewish new year.
In the secondary markets, the Nasdaq composite outperformed other leading
indices, climbing 4.80 to 764.28 on the back of a firming trend in
technology stocks. The American SE composite managed to add 0.68 at 455.32.
The morning brought a smattering of second-tier economic data, none of which
had much influence on market sentiment.
In a mildly unfavourable development, the Labor Department revised downwards
its estimate of the decline in second-quarter non-farm productivity to 2.5
per cent, the largest drop since the first three months of 1989. Meanwhile,
the increase in unit labour costs were revised upwards to 3.4 per cent,
suggesting stronger inflationary pressures.
That news, coupled with higher commodity prices, offered bond traders no
encouragement to buy ahead of Friday's keenly awaited producer price data.
As a consequence, the long end of the Treasury yield curve suffered moderate
losses, with many accounts preferring to stay on the sidelines until after
the release of the inflation report.
After a static morning, the similar trend was evident among the Dow
industrials. The decline was led by DuPont, off Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 58
7/8 , and United Technologies, down Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 33.
In the oil group, Texaco gained Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 62 1/8 , while Arco
jumped Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 106 3/8 .
The retailing sector showed a spark of life. Circuit City Stores, a home
electronics chain, climbed Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 26 after announcing that
sales in outlets opened at least a year had risen 16 per cent last month.
The company also forecast a 27 per cent surge in net income in its current
fiscal quarter.
On the negative side, shares in Jones Apparel dropped Dollars 2 to Dollars
23 1/8 on a downgrading by Merrill Lynch. The company's outlook was clouded
by the resignation of its president, announced a day earlier.
Warner-Lambert, the drugs and consumer products marketer, continued to be
buffeted by takeover speculation. Yesterday profit-takers prevailed, pushing
it down Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 80 3/4 .
The technology sector was the liveliest of a rather lacklustre lot. Stocks
across the board were showing solid gains, although analysts were unable to
link the improvement to any specific development. In semiconductors, Texas
Instruments improved Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 75 1/2 .
On the Nasdaq, Lotus Development jumped Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 44 1/2 ,
Cyrix added Dollars 2 1/4 at Dollars 40 1/8 and Intel appreciated Dollars 1
1/8 to Dollars 66 3/8 .
Canada
A late afternoon rally on the Toronto market erased more than half of an
early fall for the TSE 300 index, which finished a net 8.10 down at 4,339.07
after touching 4,327.43.
Declines finally led gains by 399 to 366 after moderate volume of 59.3m
shares.
An analyst said that besides the traditional September doldrums, the
upcoming release of August inflation figures - the US producer price index
on Friday and Canada's consumer price index next week - and next Monday's
election in Quebec could make for a lacklustre market this week.
Nine of the 14 sub-indices were lower, with chemical and forestry shares
leading the declines while transportation and conglomerates were the best
performers. The golds group built on Tuesday's rise, adding 0.3 per cent as
the New York spot bullion price put on USDollars 2 at USDollars 390.25 an
ounce.
Mexico
Shares closed higher in a continuation of the technical rebound that began
on Tuesday after eight straight losing sessions.
The IPC index moved forward 34.85, or 1.29 per cent, to 2,738.92 as the
market ignored a third consecutive weekly rise in the bellwether 28-day
cetes - or treasury bill - rates.
</TEXT>
