<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / New Sharp microwave smells success in the kitchen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW DERRINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOUGHBOROUGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sharp, the Japanese electronics group, is to install an electronic nose into
microwave ovens manufactured at its plant in Wrexham in north Wales.
Smell sensors in the oven will feed information into a neural network
programmed to recognise the characteristics of different foods when they are
cooked.
Neural networks are computers, inspired by models of the brain, that can be
built to recognise complex patterns.
Sharp is refusing to discuss its new product before its official
announcement on Monday, but journalists who have a smell of the story expect
to be told that it will mean the end of the over-cooked and dried up food
that inexperienced cooks find all too easy to produce with current
microwaves.
The advantage of using a neural network is that cooking is a complex process
and it is difficult to decide when it is complete. Even the same kind of
food needs different amounts of cooking depending on its size and shape. For
example thick steaks need to be cooked for longer than thin steaks.
Several different types of information - on temperature, colour and smell -
are needed to know that cooking is done, and of course different cooks have
different views on what constitutes rare, medium or well-done.
The neural network will be programmed in the factory, so the microwave will
arrive in the home already knowing how Sharp thinks food should be cooked.
It is not known whether it will be adjustable for vegetables al dente.
Sharp's plant in Wrexham, which opened in 1975, manufactures microwaves,
VCRs, typewriters, and word processors. It employs 1,300 people, and
production in the last financial period was valued at Pounds 120m according
to Mr Mike Williams, director of personnel and general affairs.
Sharp had been planning a press conference in Wrexham on Monday to announce
the new microwave, with the company's president, Mr Haruo Tsuji, flying in
from Japan to make the announcement. A government minister was also thought
to be scheduled to attend.
But information about the new product leaked out at the British Association
festival of science in Loughborough yesterday, at a meeting to discuss
applications of neural networks.
Asked about the announcement, Ms Caroline Barratt, head of public relations
for Sharp UK said: 'As far as Sharp is concerned we have a press conference
on Monday.'
Conference reports, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
