<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Swans song played out on proud Tyneside: Why the receivers
have lost faith in the future of the shipbuilder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If a committed workforce, a fine reputation and a proud history could
guarantee a commercial future, the Tyneside shipbuilder Swan Hunter should
be looking ahead with confidence.
But none of these things can compensate for lack of orders, or for lack of
the financial and political muscle on which orders may depend.
This week's news from receivers Price Waterhouse that the prospects of sale
as a going concern are remote, and that it would start considering offers
for the piecemeal sale of assets, signals the end of Swan Hunter, barring
some unexpected last-minute intervention.
The impending closure is a body blow for the company's loyal and skilled
workforce, its suppliers and Tyneside's economy.
In the 1980s Swan Hunter underwent a radical change in working practices and
heavy job losses. But no amount of pruning and workforce flexibility could
overcome more fundamental difficulties.
The management buy-out team which privatised Swans in 1986 did not have
access to adequate financial reserves to withstand the reduction in UK
defence orders - or the government's increasing emphasis on driving down
costs and passing financial risks on to contractors by imposing large
performance guarantees.
The buy-out team knew it needed to break into export markets to reduce
reliance on UK defence contracts, but in spite of expensive and sustained
effort it failed to win export orders for new ships.
But the Pounds 5m for which the government sold Swan Hunter to the buy-out
team should have given pause for thought compared with privatisation prices
of other warship yards in the mid-1980s. Vosper Thornycroft was sold for
Pounds 18.5m, Yarrow for Pounds 34m and VSEL/Cammell Laird for Pounds 100m,
with Pounds 60m payable initially.
Within weeks of the buy-out Swans failed to win an order for a Ministry of
Defence auxiliary oiler replenishment vessel. It went to Harland and Wolff
in politically sensitive Belfast. In 1991, completion of the British
Antarctic Survey ship cost Swans Pounds 17m, wiping out reserves. On
receivership in May 1993 it had a net debt of Pounds 51m.
Of the other privatised warship yards Yarrow on the Clyde has the financial
security of being owned by the conglomerate GEC.
VSEL in Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria, has a financial cushion from its Trident
nuclear submarine programme and a tactical alliance with Norwegian-owned
Clydeside merchant shipbuilder Kvaerner which helped VSEL win the helicopter
carrier whose loss sent Swans into receivership.
On the south coast Vosper Thornycroft is underpinned by an extremely strong
export performance.
Cammell Laird in Birkenhead was closed by VSEL last year, after a failed
search for a buyer.
The government's insistence that it would like to see Swan Hunter survive,
but must follow the rules of competitive tendering, has a hollow ring for
Swans' supporters.
They point to the guaranteed 12-year MoD refit workload promised last year
to the Rosyth dockyard as evidence that, where the political will exists,
rules can bend.
They say that Swans, in a Labour-dominated area with only one Tory MP, has
not enjoyed the support given to areas where the Conservatives have more at
stake.
Mr Peter Chapman, one of Swans' union campaigners, said: 'They'd prefer to
sacrifice Trotter's seat rather than Rifkind's' The Edinburgh Pentland seat
of Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, is not far from Rosyth.
Nor has the government accepted the argument that Swans' closure will create
monopolies in capability, driving up prices.
None of Swans' competitors wants to be seen dancing on its grave but,
quietly, the view is expressed that the shrinking MoD order-book could
simply not sustain four warship yards. VSEL says orders from the government
are enough to support a maximum of three.
The question now is whether it can sustain that many.
</TEXT>
