<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Profit-pay cut angers unions at LWT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions at London Weekend Television, a subsidiary of the Granada Group,
yesterday expressed anger at the imposition of a sharp cut in profit-related
pay at the London ITV company.
Staff were told 3 per cent of LWT's 1994-95 profits would be divided among
staff as profit-related pay for the financial year starting on October 1.
The pool for the current year is 7 per cent, and it was 8 per cent last
year.
The cut in profit-related pay comes less than two months after Granada
integrated the non-programme making activities of Granada Television and
LWT, causing the loss of between 150 and 200 jobs from a combined staff of
2,000. To sweeten the pill, staff will be paid monthly 'on account' 4 per
cent of their qualifying salary from the eventual total of profit-related
pay.
LWT staff were warned by Mr Michael Southgate, deputy managing director,
that the longer-term aim was to work towards a common Granada/LWT
profit-related pay scheme. LWT staff fear this may cause a further erosion.
There is also concern that possible cuts in management bonuses at LWT will
adversely affect a forthcoming issue of employee shares. Top LWT managers,
many of them millionaires from a management share scheme, agreed to make
money available to fund an employee share scheme. Not all the money has been
handed over and reduced bonuses may hinder the process.
</TEXT>
