<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Banham sets out Shropshire split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Telford should be given an all-purpose unitary authority, and the other five
district councils in Shropshire should be merged to form one large
authority, the Local Government Commission recommended yesterday.
It said this was the only alternative to the current two-tier position,
which splits responsibility for services between Shropshire County Council
and six district councils. Local people will be consulted about the options
over the next two months.
The commission, chaired by Sir John Banham, estimated that creating the two
unitaries would cost between Pounds 13m and Pounds 16m, but would eventually
save Pounds 4m to Pounds 6m annually.
Under the plan, Wrekin district, dominated by the new town of Telford, would
split away from the rest of the county, which would be labelled
'Shropshire'. The commission will also consult on extending Wrekin to the
south to take in seven parishes from Bridgnorth district.
This option provoked fierce opposition from local politicians, because the
county and four of the districts had all supported leaving the two-tier
system intact.
Many had expected the commission to recommend making Telford unitary and
maintaining the status quo in the rest of the county.
The cross-party Association of District Councils welcomed the proposals for
Wrekin. However, it said a single authority for the rest of Shropshire would
be too remote to represent the views of local people properly.
The district councils of Bridgnorth, Oswestry and North and South Shropshire
all said they would prefer the two-tier status quo to this option, although
Shrewsbury &amp; Atcham favoured unitaries.
The Labour-led Association of County Councils said residents had been given
a 'fair choice' between a unitary option and keeping the status quo. It said
'questions must be asked about the viability of a unitary authority based on
the Wrekin', because the new organisation would be too small.
</TEXT>
