<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Clarke and George tackle rates conundrum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank
of England, yesterday reviewed official interest rates as most City analysts
predicted that they would stay unchanged for the time being.
But the possibility of an eventual rise in base rates from their current
5.25 per cent was underlined by the Treasury's latest monthly monetary
report. It said recent indicators pointed to a further strengthening of
economic activity.
The report, prepared for the meeting of the two men, highlighted the dilemma
facing the Treasury and Bank. On the one hand underlying inflation was at
its lowest for 27 years in July and the broadest inflation measure - the
gross domestic product deflator - at its lowest for 31 years in the second
quarter. But growth - revised up to 3.7 per cent in the year to the second
quarter - was the strongest since the final quarter of 1988.
The report said: 'Monthly indicators point to a further strengthening of
activity.' It cited continuing growth in retail sales, manufacturing output,
output expectations and falling unemployment.
Yesterday Halifax Building Society, the UK's biggest mortgage lender, voiced
its fears about the impact of an interest rate increase on the fragile
recovery in the housing market. Announcing the society's interim results, Mr
Jon Foulds, chairman, said that consumer confidence was lagging well behind
the upturn shown in official statistics. He said: 'We are concerned that any
rise in interest rates would damage a very delicately poised housing market
recovery.'
Mr David Gilchrist, corporate development manager, said the society was
expecting some recovery in the autumn. But if interest rates and perhaps
taxes rose at about Budget time in late November, the housing market could
remain depressed through the start of next year.
As usual, the Treasury report gave no insight into official thinking on
interest rates while officials refused to comment on yesterday's meeting.
But City analysts suggested that Mr Clarke would be unlikely to opt for a
pre-emptive interest rate rise at this stage and might prefer to wait for
November, when next month's Conservative party conference will be safely out
of the way.
The next Clarke/George monetary meeting will be on September 26. That will
allow Mr Clarke to attend the Commonwealth finance ministers' meeting in
Malta late this month and the annual meetings of the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank soon after.
Halifax results, Page 25
</TEXT>
