<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Business channel aimed at City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Flextech, the fast-growing media group controlled by Tele-Communications,
the largest cable television operator in the US, and Dow Jones, publisher of
the Wall Street Journal, will today announce the creation of a European
Business Channel.
It is believed that the two companies are prepared to invest as much as
Dollars 50m (Pounds 32.2m) in the venture and that an agreement has been
reached with Videotron, the cable company, to carry the service to the City
of London.
The London-based channel, to be launched in the first quarter of next year,
will start transmitting 18 hours a day before moving to a 24-hour-a-day
service. It will be carried on the Eutelsat satellite system and will
broadcast to cable networks and satellite dishes all over Europe.
The plan is to launch a dual service - a conventional service of business
news and features with material from Dow Jones business television channels
in the US and the Asian Business Channel in which TCI is an investor.
There will also be a more specialist digital service to be broadcast direct
to the computer screens of market professionals.
This is likely to compete with Reuters Financial Television, which runs a
service aimed at foreign exchange, debt and treasury financial markets in
London.
