<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Democratic Unionists to consider options
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Rev Ian Paisley stood on home territory yesterday, still fuming after
his Downing Street confrontation with Mr John Major.
Outside the Democratic Unionist party's headquarters in East Belfast Mr
Paisley was cheered by a dozen flag-waving supporters. He said he had no
immediate plans to call for a campaign of unionist civil protest. 'I am not
calling on my supporters to take to the streets,' he said. 'We shall be
putting forward practical plans for a Unionist forum.'
The unionist newspaper The Newsletter said it had been inundated with calls
from readers registering disgust at the way Mr Paisley had been treated in
Downing Street. But many unionists were critical of Mr Paisley's position. A
number of senior members of the Ulster Unionist party, including Mr Jim
Wilson, its general secretary, said the DUP leader was undermining the
unionist cause.
Mr John Hume, leader of the Social Democratic and Labour party, and Mr Gerry
Adams are given more credit for achieving the IRA ceasefire than the British
and Irish premiers according to a Gallup poll in today's Daily Telegraph. Mr
Hume scores 27 per cent, Mr Adams 22 per cent, Mr Albert Reynolds 18 per
cent and Mr Major 12 per cent.
