<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Paisley blasts 'dictator' Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELFAST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Rev Ian Paisley stood on home territory yesterday, still fuming after
his Downing Street confrontation with Mr John Major.
In a characteristically inflammatory press conference at the new east
Belfast headquarters of the Democratic Unionist party, which he leads, Mr
Paisley referred angrily to the way Mr Major abruptly ended their meeting on
Tuesday.
Flanked by DUP MPs Mr Paisley was cheered by a dozen flag-waving supporters
as he bluntly refused to answer questions from journalists from Irish
nationalist papers and barked abuse at agency and national television
reporters.
He stepped up his war of words with the British government by equating the
prime minister with Hitler. 'It was the stance of a dictator who says that
either you believe me or you go to the gas chambers,' he said. He reiterated
his hardline opposition to the UK-Irish peace process.
At the Downing Street meeting Mr Major repeatedly interrupted Mr Paisley's
attempt to read a long statement on the political situation in Northern
Ireland.
Yesterday Mr Paisley demanded a retraction from a national television
channel which reported that he had locked himself in a Downing Street
lavatory. He said he had read the remainder of his statement to a civil
servant after Mr Major, with two Northern Ireland Office ministers, had
abruptly left the meeting.
He again refused to accept Mr Major's reassurances that there had been no
secret deals with the IRA as part of last week's ceasefire announcement, and
accused the UK and Irish governments being part of 'a conspiracy' to take
Ulster out of the UK.
Mr Paisley said he had no immediate plans to call for a campaign of Unionist
civil protest, as he did in opposition to the Hillsborough agreement in the
1980s. 'I am not calling on my supporters to take to the streets,' he said.
'We shall be putting forward practical plans for a Unionist forum.'
Many unionists outside the DUP were critical yesterday of Mr Paisley's
position. A number of senior members of the Ulster Unionist party, including
its general secretary, Mr Jim Wilson, said the DUP leader was undermining
the Unionist cause at a crucial time in the province's political history.
But the unionist newspaper The Newsletter said it had been inundated with
calls from readers registering disgust at the way Mr Paisley had been
treated in Downing Street.
</TEXT>
