<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Mandela urges halt to strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Nelson Mandela yesterday appealed to South African workers to curb
their right to strike following a recent spate of industrial stoppages that
threatened the country's development by frightening away foreign investment,
agencies report from Johannesburg.
Mr Mandela, speaking at the national convention of the Congress of South
Africa Trade Unions, said: 'There are at least 5m people who are unemployed,
who don't know where to find food, who don't know where to find a place to
sleep. That is your problem to solve.'
He urged the 1,700 union delegates not to look at their own personal
interest or those of their unions but to 'create conditions where business
can expand' and jobs be created.
Meanwhile, car industry workers streamed back to work yesterday after a
five-week strike. Assembly lines opened in all but one of South Africa's
seven car plants after the union decided to restart pay talks.
Since June there have also been strikes and walkouts in the metal, paper,
mining, oil, and road freight industries. The South African Chamber of
Business has put the cumulative loss of production as a result of recent
strikes at about R3bn (Pounds 535m), or 0.5 per cent of gross domestic
product.
